{
  "text": "This growing interest is reflected in an increasing number of systematic reviews on the prevalence of near miss [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The reported prevalence has ranged overall from less than 1 per 1000 live births to 82 per 1000 live births, with rates in resource poor settings ranging from four to eight percent of hospital-based deliveries [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . [CITATION_6] reports a mean for near miss cases of 8 per 1000 live births [CITATION_7] . The variation is largely due to differences in the populations studied, but also in the definitions used. Near miss are not easy to define, and definitions have relied on a variety of approaches, including criteria of organ dysfunction; criteria of clinical management such as admission to intensive care; signs and symptoms; or clinical entities such as eclampsia or uterine rupture [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
